        {
            "body": "Ah checking the datatype defined in the json might be a hard I guess yeah. I'm not sure if hardcoding the checking function of every datatype is going to make it easier.\r\n\r\nThe problem with these checking functions is that you can't really define a standard by saying \"here is an implementation of it, read the code and do the same thing\".\r\n\r\nBut yeah ok, I see your point about .json defined types, json schemas are probably not enough to specify datatypes like that.\r\n\r\nprotocol buffers do have a specification (https://developers.google.com/protocol-buffers/docs/reference/proto3-spec), we might be able to do something similar.\r\n\r\nEdit: ah but, yes it's possible to do it with json schemas, all you have to do is let the user give its own \"usage\" schema for each new datatype\r\n\r\nI don't like too much the fact that a datatype could be used in \"any json valid way\" though. That seems kind of hard to handle by protodef implementations.",
